India, officially the Republic of India, &#91;j&#93; &#91;20&#93; is a country tucked away in [South Asia](/South_Asia). It’s the [seventh-largest country by area](/List_of_countries_and_dependencies_by_area), and since 2023, the undisputed champion of population, the [most populous country](/List_of_countries_by_population_(United_Nations)). And since its rather dramatic independence in 1947, it’s also held the title of the world's most populous democracy, a rather noisy achievement. &#91;22&#93; &#91;23&#93; &#91;24&#93;

Imagine this: the [Indian Ocean](/Indian_Ocean) brooding to the south, the [Arabian Sea](/Arabian_Sea) a dark mirror to the southwest, and the [Bay of Bengal](/Bay_of_Bengal) a restless expanse to the southeast. Land borders? Oh yes, it shares them with [Pakistan](/Pakistan) to the west; &#91;k&#93; [China](/China), [Nepal](/Nepal), and [Bhutan](/Bhutan) to the north; and [Bangladesh](/Bangladesh) and [Myanmar](/Myanmar) to the east. Even out in the [Indian Ocean](/Indian_Ocean), India’s presence is felt, near [Sri Lanka](/Sri_Lanka) and the [Maldives](/Maldives). Its [Andaman and Nicobar Islands](/Andaman_and_Nicobar_Islands) even flirt with maritime borders with Myanmar, [Thailand](/Thailand), and [Indonesia](/Indonesia).

### History

**Ancient India**

Humans, the *Homo sapiens* variety, apparently arrived on the [Indian subcontinent](/Indian_subcontinent) from [Africa](/Africa) no later than 55,000 years ago. &#91;26&#93; &#91;27&#93; &#91;28&#93; Their prolonged stay, largely in isolation, has fostered a rather bewildering diversity, like a gardener who forgot to prune. &#91;29&#93; By 9,000 years ago, settled life began to sprout on the subcontinent’s western edges, near the [Indus](/Indus_River) [river basin](/River_basin). This gradually morphed into the sophisticated [Indus Valley Civilisation](/Indus_Valley_Civilisation) of the third millennium BCE. &#91;30&#93;

By 1200 BCE, a rather archaic version of [Sanskrit](/Sanskrit), that grand [Indo-European language](/Indo-European_language), had drifted in from the northwest. &#91;31&#93; &#91;32&#93; Its ancient hymns whisper of the nascent stirrings of [Hinduism](/Hinduism) in India. &#91;33&#93; Meanwhile, India's original [Dravidian languages](/Dravidian_languages) were, it seems, politely nudged aside in the northern territories. &#91;34&#93; By 400 BCE, the rather rigid [caste](/Caste) system had taken root within Hinduism, and the philosophical rebels [Buddhism](/History_of_Buddhism_in_India) and [Jainism](/History_of_Jainism) had emerged, preaching social orders not bound by the accident of birth. &#91;36&#93; Early political entities, like the [Maurya](/Maurya_Empire) and [Gupta Empires](/Gupta_Empire), were rather loosely knit empires. &#91;37&#93; This era saw a flourishing of creativity, &#91;38&#93; but also a noticeable decline in the status of women &#91;39&#93; and the systematization of [untouchability](/Untouchability). &#91;l&#93; &#91;40&#93; In [South India](/South_India), the [Middle kingdoms](/Middle_kingdoms_of_India) diligently exported their Dravidian language scripts and religious ideas to the burgeoning kingdoms of [Southeast Asia](/Southeast_Asia). &#91;41&#93;

The first millennium CE saw the quiet arrival of [Christianity](/Christianity), [Islam](/Islam), [Judaism](/Judaism), and [Zoroastrianism](/Zoroastrianism) along India's southern and western coasts. &#91;42&#93; As the second millennium dawned, Muslim armies from [Central Asia](/Central_Asia) began their intermittent incursions into India's northern plains. &#91;43&#93; The subsequent [Delhi Sultanate](/Delhi_Sultanate) managed to pull much of North India into the vibrant, cosmopolitan tapestry of medieval Islam. &#91;44&#93; In the south, the [Vijayanagara Empire](/Vijayanagara_Empire) cultivated a durable, composite Hindu culture. &#91;45&#93; And in the [Punjab](/Punjab), [Sikhism](/Sikhism) quietly bloomed, a rejection of institutionalized religion. &#91;46&#93; The [Mughal Empire](/Mughal_Empire) then arrived, ushering in two centuries of economic growth and a fragile peace, &#91;47&#93; leaving behind a rather impressive architectural legacy. &#91;48&#93; &#91;49&#93; The slow, steady expansion of the [British East India Company](/Company_rule_in_India) began to twist India into a colonial economy, but also, ironically, consolidated its own grip on [sovereignty](/Sovereignty). &#91;50&#93; Then came the [British Crown rule](/British_Raj) in 1858. The rights that were so readily promised to Indians trickled in at a glacial pace, &#91;51&#93; &#91;52&#93; but the introduction of technological advancements and the slow bloom of modern ideas about education and public life began to take root. &#91;53&#93; And from this fertile ground, a [nationalist movement](/Indian_independence_movement) emerged, the first of its kind in the non-European [British Empire](/British_Empire), and a ripple that would influence other nationalist movements. &#91;54&#93; &#91;55&#93; Known for its commitment to nonviolent resistance after 1920, &#91;56&#93; it ultimately became the driving force behind the end of British rule. &#91;57&#93; In 1947, the [British Indian Empire](/British_Raj) was carved into two independent [dominions](/Dominion), &#91;58&#93; &#91;59&#93; &#91;60&#93; &#91;61&#93; India, with its Hindu majority, and Pakistan, with its Muslim majority. This seismic shift was accompanied by a staggering loss of life and an unprecedented human migration. &#91;62&#93;

Since 1950, India has been a [federal republic](/Federal_republic), operating under a democratic [parliamentary system](/Parliamentary_system). It’s a society that’s decidedly [pluralistic](/Pluralism_(political_philosophy)), proudly [multilingual](/Multilingualism), and richly [multi-ethnic](/Multiculturalism). The population, which was a mere 361 million in 1951, has swelled to over 1.4 billion by 2023. &#91;63&#93; In that same span, its nominal [per capita income](/Per_capita_income) has limped from US$64 annually to US$2,601, and its literacy rate has climbed from a dismal 16.6% to a more respectable 74%. A nation that was, by all accounts, rather destitute in 1951, &#91;64&#93; India has transformed into a major, fast-growing economy &#91;List_of_countries_by_real_GDP_growth_rate&#93;, a veritable hub for information technology services, &#91;Information_technology_in_India&#93; and boasts an ever-expanding middle class. &#91;65&#93; While India has managed to reduce its [poverty rate](/Poverty_in_India), it’s done so at the cost of widening economic inequality. &#91;66&#93; It’s also a nuclear-weapon state &#91;List_of_states_with_nuclear_weapons&#93; that ranks rather high in military expenditure. &#91;List_of_countries_by_military_expenditures&#93; And then there are the lingering disputes over [Kashmir](/Kashmir) with its neighbours, Pakistan and China, unresolved since the mid-20th century. &#91;67&#93; Among the persistent socio-economic hurdles India grapples with are [gender inequality](/Gender_inequality_in_India), pervasive [child malnutrition](/Malnutrition_in_India), &#91;68&#93; and a rather alarming rise in [air pollution](/Air_pollution_in_India). &#91;69&#93; Yet, India’s land is a marvel of [megadiversity](/Megadiverse_country), boasting four distinct [biodiversity hotspots](/Biodiversity_hotspots). &#91;70&#93; India's wildlife, traditionally treated with a certain tolerance within its culture, &#91;71&#93; is now finding refuge in a growing network of [protected habitats](/Protected_areas_of_India).

### Etymology

According to the [Oxford English Dictionary](/Oxford_English_Dictionary), the English word "India" originates from the [Classical Latin](/Classical_Latin) *India*, a rather vague geographical designation for a vast Asian region stretching from [South Asia](/South_Asia) all the way to China's borders. Its deeper roots lie in [Hellenistic Greek](/Hellenistic_Greek) *India* (Ἰνδία), and further back still to [Ancient Greek](/Ancient_Greek) *Indos* (Ἰνδός), referring to the mighty River [Indus](/Indus). Then we have the Achaemenian [Old Persian](/Old_Persian) *Hindu* (an eastern province of the [Achaemenid Empire](/Achaemenid_Empire)), and finally, the [Sanskrit](/Sanskrit) *Sindhu*, meaning "river," but more specifically, the Indus River, and by extension, its densely populated basin. &#91;72&#93; The [Ancient Greeks](/Ancient_Greeks) referred to the inhabitants of South Asia as *Indoi*, meaning 'the people of the Indus'. &#91;73&#93;

The name [Bharat](/Names_for_India), mentioned in both [Indian epic poetry](/Indian_epic_poetry) and the very [Constitution of India](/Constitution_of_India), &#91;74&#93; &#91;75&#93; is used in various forms across [many Indian languages](/Names_for_India). It’s a modern interpretation of the ancient name *Bharatavarsha*, which initially designated [North India], &#91;76&#93; &#91;77&#93; and Bharat gained significant traction from the mid-19th century as a native term for India. &#91;74&#93; &#91;78&#93;

[Hindustan](/Hindustan) (pronounced [&#91;ɦɪndʊˈstaːn&#93;](/Help:IPA/Hindi_and_Urdu) [ⓘ](/File:Hindustan.ogg) ), a name with [Middle Persian](/Middle_Persian) origins, became popular by the 13th century, &#91;79&#93; and has been widely used since the era of the [Mughal Empire](/Mughal_Empire). The meaning of Hindustan has shifted over time, referring to a region encompassing the northern [Indian subcontinent](/Indian_subcontinent) (which includes present-day northern India and [Pakistan](/Pakistan)) or, at other times, to India in its near entirety. &#91;74&#93; &#91;78&#93; &#91;80&#93;

### History

**Ancient India**

A manuscript illustration, circa 1650, depicting the Sanskrit epic [Ramayana](/Ramayana), a story composed between approximately 400 BCE and 300 CE. &#91;81&#93;

Fifty-five thousand years ago, the first modern humans, *Homo sapiens*, made their way onto the Indian subcontinent from Africa. &#91;26&#93; &#91;27&#93; &#91;28&#93; The earliest tangible evidence of modern human presence in South Asia dates back roughly 30,000 years. &#91;26&#93; After 6500 BCE, signs of domesticating food crops and animals, constructing permanent dwellings, and storing surplus grain began to appear in [Mehrgarh](/Mehrgarh) and other sites in [Balochistan, Pakistan](/Balochistan,_Pakistan). &#91;82&#93; These developments gradually gave rise to the [Indus Valley Civilisation](/Indus_Valley_Civilisation), &#91;83&#93; &#91;82&#93; the first urban culture to grace South Asia, &#91;84&#93; flourishing between 2500–1900 BCE across Pakistan and western India. &#91;85&#93; Centered in cities like [Mohenjo-daro](/Mohenjo-daro), [Harappa](/Harappa), [Dholavira](/Dholavira), and [Kalibangan], and supported by diverse subsistence strategies, this civilization was deeply involved in craft production and extensive trade networks. &#91;84&#93;

During the period from 2000 to 500 BCE, many regions of the subcontinent saw a transition from [Chalcolithic](/Chalcolithic) cultures to those of the [Iron Age](/Iron_Age). &#91;86&#93; The [Vedas](/Vedas), the most ancient scriptures associated with [Hinduism](/Hinduism), &#91;87&#93; were composed during this era, &#91;88&#93; and historians have used them to reconstruct the existence of a [Vedic culture](/Vedic_period) in the [Punjab region](/Punjab_region) and the upper [Gangetic Plain](/Indo-Gangetic_Plain). &#91;86&#93; The majority of historians also believe this period witnessed several waves of [Indo-Aryan migration](/Indo-Aryan_migration) into the subcontinent from the northwest. &#91;87&#93; The [caste system], which established a hierarchy of priests, warriors, and free peasants, while also marginalizing indigenous peoples by deeming their occupations impure, began to form during this time. &#91;89&#93; On the [Deccan Plateau](/Deccan_Plateau), archaeological findings from this period hint at a chiefdom stage of political organization. &#91;86&#93; In [South India](/South_India), evidence of a shift towards sedentary living is marked by the numerous [megalithic](/Megalith) monuments dating from this period, &#91;90&#93; alongside traces of [agriculture], [irrigation tanks](/Irrigation_tanks), and established craft traditions. &#91;90&#93;

Cave 26 of the rock-cut [Ajanta Caves](/Ajanta_Caves)

In the latter part of the Vedic period, around the 6th century BCE, the small states and chiefdoms dotting the Ganges Plain and the northwestern regions coalesced into 16 significant oligarchies and monarchies known collectively as the [mahajanapadas](/Mahajanapadas). &#91;91&#93; &#91;92&#93; This burgeoning urbanisation spurred the rise of non-Vedic religious movements, two of which eventually evolved into distinct religions. [Jainism](/Jainism) gained prominence during the lifetime of its key figure, [Mahavira](/Mahavira). &#91;93&#93; [Buddhism](/Buddhism), founded on the teachings of [Gautama Buddha](/Gautama_Buddha), began to attract followers from all social strata, with the exception of the middle class; the chronicles of the Buddha's life are central to the earliest recorded history of India. &#91;94&#93; &#91;95&#93; &#91;96&#93;

In an era marked by increasing urban affluence, both religions championed [renunciation](/Nekkhamma) as a core ideal, &#91;97&#93; and both established enduring monastic traditions. Politically, by the 3rd century BCE, the kingdom of [Magadha](/Magadha_(Mahajanapada)) had managed to annex or subdue its rivals, emerging as the [Maurya Empire](/Maurya_Empire). &#91;98&#93; While it was once believed the empire spanned most of the subcontinent, excluding only the far south, current scholarship suggests its core territories were interspersed with large, autonomous regions. &#91;99&#93; &#91;100&#93; The Mauryan rulers are recognized as much for their imperial ambitions and meticulous management of public affairs as for [Ashoka]'s subsequent [renunciation](/Renunciation) of militarism and his widespread advocacy of the Buddhist [dhamma](/Dharma_(Buddhism)). &#91;101&#93; &#91;102&#93;

The [Sangam literature](/Sangam_literature) of the [Tamil language](/Tamil_language) provides insight into the period between 200 BCE and 200 CE, during which the southern peninsula was governed by the [Cheras](/Chera_dynasty), the [Cholas](/Chola_dynasty), and the [Pandyas](/Pandya_dynasty). These dynasties engaged in extensive [traded extensively with the Roman Empire](/Indo-Roman_trade_relations) and with both [West](/Western_Asia) and [Southeast Asia](/Southeast_Asia). &#91;103&#93; &#91;104&#93; In North India, Hinduism solidified its patriarchal hold within the family structure, leading to a greater subjugation of women. &#91;105&#93; &#91;98&#93; By the 4th and 5th centuries, the [Gupta Empire](/Gupta_Empire) had established a sophisticated system of administration and taxation across the greater Ganges Plain; this framework served as a model for subsequent Indian kingdoms. &#91;106&#93; &#91;107&#93; Under the Guptas, a revitalized Hinduism, emphasizing devotion over ritualistic administration, began to gain prominence. &#91;108&#93; This resurgence was reflected in a flourishing of [sculpture](/Sculpture_in_the_Indian_subcontinent) and [architecture](/Architecture_of_India), which found patronage among the urban elite. &#91;107&#93; Classical [Sanskrit literature](/Sanskrit_literature) also experienced a golden age, and Indian [science](/History_of_science_and_technology_in_the_Indian_subcontinent), [astronomy](/Indian_astronomy), [medicine](/Ayurveda), and [mathematics](/Indian_mathematics) made significant strides. &#91;107&#93;

**Medieval India**

The [Brihadeshwara temple](/Brihadeshwara_temple) in [Thanjavur](/Thanjavur), completed in 1010 CE.
The [Qutub Minar](/Qutub_Minar), standing at 73 meters (240 ft) tall, was completed by the [Sultan of Delhi](/Sultan_of_Delhi), [Iltutmish](/Iltutmish).

The early medieval period of India, spanning from 600 to 1200 CE, is characterized by a mosaic of regional kingdoms and a rich cultural diversity. &#91;109&#93; When [Harsha](/Harsha) of [Kannauj](/Kannauj), who ruled a significant portion of the Indo-Gangetic Plain from 606 to 647 CE, attempted to push his ambitions southward, he was decisively defeated by the [Chalukya](/Chalukya_dynasty) ruler of the Deccan. &#91;110&#93; His successor's attempt to expand eastward met a similar fate, being defeated by the [Pala](/Pala_Empire) king of [Bengal](/Bengal). &#91;110&#93; When the Chalukyas tried to advance southward, they were repelled by the [Pallavas](/Pallava_dynasty) from further south, who in turn faced opposition from the [Pandyas](/Pandya_dynasty) and the [Cholas](/Chola_dynasty) from even further south. &#91;110&#93; No single ruler during this era managed to forge a lasting empire that consistently controlled territories beyond their immediate region. &#91;109&#93; During this time, pastoral communities, displaced by the expansion of the agricultural economy, were integrated into the caste society, as were new ruling elites who did not adhere to traditional lineages. &#91;111&#93; Consequently, the caste system began to exhibit regional variations. &#91;111&#93;

In the 6th and 7th centuries, the earliest [devotional hymns](/Bhakti) emerged in the Tamil language. &#91;112&#93; These compositions were emulated across India, contributing to both the resurgence of Hinduism and the development of all [modern languages of the subcontinent](/Languages_of_India). &#91;112&#93; Indian royalty, from the most powerful to the minor rulers, along with the temples they patronized, drew significant numbers of citizens to their capital cities, which also became vital economic centers. &#91;113&#93; Temple towns of varying sizes began to proliferate throughout the land as India experienced another wave of urbanization. &#91;113&#93; By the 8th and 9th centuries, the influence of these developments extended into Southeast Asia, with South Indian culture and political systems being disseminated to regions that now form modern-day [Myanmar](/Myanmar), [Thailand](/Thailand), [Laos](/Laos), [Brunei](/Brunei), [Cambodia](/Cambodia), [Vietnam](/Vietnam), [Philippines](/Philippines), [Malaysia](/Malaysia), and [Indonesia](/Indonesia). &#91;114&#93; Indian merchants, scholars, and occasionally military forces played a role in this cultural transmission; Southeast Asians also initiated this process, with many undertaking studies in Indian institutions and translating Buddhist and Hindu texts into their own languages. &#91;114&#93;

Following the 10th century, nomadic Central Asian clans, adept at using [swift-horse](/Courser_(horse)) cavalry and assembling vast armies united by shared ethnicity and religion, repeatedly raided South Asia's northwestern plains. This culminated in the establishment of the Islamic [Delhi Sultanate](/Delhi_Sultanate) in 1206. &#91;115&#93; The sultanate eventually controlled a substantial portion of North India and launched numerous expeditions into South India. Although initially disruptive to the established Indian elites, the sultanate largely permitted its vast non-Muslim subject population to retain their own laws and customs. &#91;116&#93; &#91;117&#93;

By successfully repelling [Mongol raiders](/Mongol_Empire) throughout the 13th century, the sultanate shielded India from the widespread devastation that afflicted West and Central Asia. This created an environment conducive to centuries of [migration](/Human_migration) of fleeing soldiers, learned individuals, mystics, traders, artists, and artisans from that region into the subcontinent, fostering a syncretic Indo-Islamic culture in the north. &#91;118&#93; &#91;119&#93; The sultanate's raiding activities and subsequent weakening of the regional kingdoms in South India paved the way for the rise of the indigenous [Vijayanagara Empire](/Vijayanagara_Empire). &#91;120&#93; Embracing a strong [Shaivite](/Shaivism) tradition and building upon the military technologies adopted from the sultanate, the empire eventually exerted control over much of peninsular India, &#91;121&#93; leaving a significant cultural imprint on South Indian society for generations to come. &#91;120&#93;

**Early modern India**

A distant view of the [Taj Mahal](/Taj_Mahal) observed from the [Agra Fort](/Agra_Fort).
A two-[mohur](/Mohur) Company gold coin, minted in 1835, bearing the inscription "[William IIII](/William_IV), King" on its [obverse](/Obverse_and_reverse).

In the early 16th century, northern India, then largely under Muslim rulers, &#91;122&#93; fell once more to the superior mobility and firepower of a new generation of Central Asian warriors. &#91;123&#93; The resulting [Mughal Empire](/Mughal_Empire) did not eradicate the local societies it came to rule. Instead, it sought to balance and pacify them through innovative administrative practices &#91;124&#93; &#91;125&#93; and the inclusion of diverse ruling elites, &#91;126&#93; leading to more systematic, centralized, and uniform governance. &#91;127&#93; Eschewing tribal affiliations and a purely Islamic identity, particularly under [Akbar], the Mughals unified their vast realms through loyalty, expressed through a Persianized culture, to an emperor who held a near-divine status. &#91;126&#93;

The Mughal state's economic policies, which derived the majority of their revenue from agriculture &#91;128&#93; and mandated tax payments in a well-regulated silver currency, &#91;129&#93; encouraged peasants and artisans to engage more actively in larger markets. &#91;127&#93; The relative peace maintained by the empire for much of the 17th century contributed to India's economic expansion, &#91;127&#93; fostering increased patronage for [painting](/Mughal_painting), literary forms, textiles, and [architecture](/Mughal_architecture). &#91;130&#93; New, cohesive social groups emerged in northern and western India, such as the [Marathas](/Maratha_Empire), the [Rajputs](/Rajput), and the [Sikhs](/Sikh_Empire). These groups developed military and governing ambitions during Mughal rule, gaining both recognition and combat experience through collaboration or conflict. &#91;131&#93; The growth of commerce during the Mughal era also led to the emergence of new Indian commercial and political elites along the coasts of southern and eastern India. &#91;131&#93; As the empire began to decline, many of these elites were able to assert greater control over their own affairs. &#91;132&#93;

By the early 18th century, as the lines between commercial and political dominance blurred, several European trading companies, including the [English East India Company](/East_India_Company), had established outposts along the coast. &#91;133&#93; &#91;134&#93; The East India Company's dominance of the seas, its greater resources, and its more advanced military training and technology enabled it to increasingly project its military power and attract a segment of the Indian elite. These factors were crucial in allowing the company to gain control of the [Bengal](/Bengal) region by 1765 and effectively sideline its European rivals. &#91;135&#93; &#91;133&#93; &#91;136&#93; &#91;137&#93; Its subsequent access to the wealth of Bengal, and the resulting increase in its military strength and size, empowered it to annex or subdue most of India by the 1820s. &#91;138&#93; India, which had long been a significant exporter of manufactured goods, now found itself supplying raw materials to the [British Empire](/British_Empire). Many historians mark this period as the beginning of India's colonial era. &#91;133&#93; By this time, with its economic power significantly curtailed by the British parliament and effectively functioning as an arm of British administration, the East India Company began to more deliberately engage in non-economic spheres, including education, social reform, and culture. &#91;139&#93;

**Modern India**

A map from 1909 depicting the [British Indian Empire](/British_Indian_Empire).

Historians generally agree that India's modern era commenced sometime between 1848 and 1885. The appointment of [Lord Dalhousie](/James_Broun-Ramsay,_1st_Marquess_of_Dalhousie) as Governor General of the East India Company in 1848 laid the groundwork for changes essential to establishing a modern state. These included the consolidation and formal demarcation of sovereignty, the systematic surveillance of the population, and the structured education of citizens. Technological innovations—such as railways, canals, and the telegraph—were introduced not long after their advent in [Europe]. &#91;140&#93; &#91;141&#93; &#91;142&#93; &#91;143&#93; Simultaneously, growing discontent with the company's rule fueled the [Indian Rebellion of 1857](/Indian_Rebellion_of_1857). Fueled by a confluence of diverse grievances and perceptions, including the intrusive nature of British social reforms, burdensome land taxes, and the arbitrary treatment of some prominent landowners and princes, the rebellion spread across many regions of northern and central India, shaking the very foundations of Company rule. &#91;144&#93; &#91;145&#93;

Although the rebellion was ultimately suppressed by 1858, it led directly to the dissolution of the East India Company and the assumption of [direct administration of India](/British_Raj) by the British government. Proclaiming a [unitary state](/Unitary_state) and establishing a gradual, albeit limited, British-style parliamentary system, the new rulers also took steps to protect the existing princes and landed aristocracy, viewing them as a feudal bulwark against future unrest. &#91;146&#93; &#91;147&#93; In the decades that followed, public life gradually began to emerge across India, eventually culminating in the founding of the [Indian National Congress](/Indian_National_Congress) (commonly referred to as the Congress) in 1885. &#91;148&#93; &#91;149&#93; &#91;150&#93; &#91;151&#93;

[Jawaharlal Nehru](/Jawaharlal_Nehru) sharing a light moment with [Mahatma Gandhi](/Mahatma_Gandhi) in Mumbai, July 6, 1946.

The rapid influx of technology and the commercialization of agriculture in the latter half of the 19th century were accompanied by significant economic setbacks, leaving many small farmers increasingly dependent on the unpredictable fluctuations of distant markets. &#91;152&#93; The frequency and severity of large-scale [famines](/Famine_in_India) increased, and despite the considerable risks borne by Indian taxpayers in developing infrastructure, minimal industrial employment was generated for the Indian population. &#91;153&#93; &#91;154&#93; There were, however, some positive outcomes: commercial agriculture, particularly in the newly irrigated Punjab region, led to an increase in food production for domestic consumption. &#91;155&#93; The expanding railway network proved crucial in providing famine relief, &#91;156&#93; significantly reduced the cost of transporting goods, &#91;156&#93; and provided vital support for nascent Indian-owned industries. &#91;155&#93;

Following [World War I](/World_War_I), during which approximately [one million Indians served](/Indian_Army_during_World_War_I), &#91;157&#93; a new era began. This period was marked by the implementation of [British reforms](/Montagu%E2%80%93Chelmsford_Reforms) but also by the imposition of [repressive legislation](/Rowlatt_act), a more assertive Indian demand for self-rule, and the nascent stages of a [nonviolent](/Nonviolent) movement of non-cooperation, spearheaded and symbolized by [Mahatma Gandhi](/Mahatma_Gandhi). &#91;158&#93; Throughout the 1930s, the British enacted slow legislative reforms, and the Indian National Congress achieved significant victories in the ensuing elections. &#91;159&#93; The subsequent decade was fraught with crises: [Indian participation in World War II](/India_in_World_War_II), the Congress's final push for non-cooperation, and a surge in [Muslim nationalism](/Muslim_nationalism_in_South_Asia). These events culminated in India's independence in 1947, but this triumph was tempered by the [partition of India](/Partition_of_India) into two separate states: India and Pakistan. &#91;160&#93;

A cornerstone of India's self-identity as an independent nation was its constitution, finalized in 1950, which established a secular and democratic republic. &#91;161&#93; Economic liberalization, initiated in the 1980s and bolstered by technical knowledge shared with the Soviet Union, &#91;162&#93; has fostered the growth of a substantial urban middle class, positioning India as one of the [world's fastest-growing economies](/List_of_countries_by_GDP_(real)_growth_rate), &#91;163&#93; and enhancing its geopolitical influence. Nevertheless, India continues to grapple with persistent poverty, both in rural and urban areas; &#91;164&#93; instances of [religious](/Religious_violence_in_India) and [caste-related violence](/Caste-related_violence_in_India); &#91;165&#93; [Maoist-inspired Naxalite insurgencies]; &#91;166&#93; and persistent [separatism in Jammu and Kashmir](/Insurgency_in_Jammu_and_Kashmir) and in [Northeast India](/Insurgency_in_Northeast_India). &#91;167&#93; India's steadfast commitment to democratic freedoms stands as a unique achievement among the world's newer nations; however, despite its recent economic triumphs, the goal of liberating its disadvantaged population from want remains elusive. &#91;169&#93;

### Geography

The [Tungabhadra](/Tungabhadra_River), with its rocky outcrops, flows into the peninsular [Krishna River](/Krishna_River). &#91;170&#93;
Fishing boats are moored together in a [tidal creek](/Creek_(tidal)) in the village of [Anjarle](/Anjarle), Maharashtra.

India occupies the vast majority of the Indian subcontinent, situated atop the [Indian tectonic plate](/Indian_Plate), itself a part of the larger [Indo-Australian Plate](/Indo-Australian_Plate). &#91;171&#93; India's defining geological processes commenced approximately 75 million years ago when the Indian Plate, then a component of the southern supercontinent [Gondwana](/Gondwana), initiated a northeastward [drift](/Plate_tectonics) driven by [seafloor spreading](/Seafloor_spreading) to its southwest, and later, to its south and southeast. &#91;171&#93; Concurrently, the immense [Tethyan](/Tethys_Ocean) [oceanic crust](/Oceanic_crust) to its northeast began to [subduct](/Subduction) beneath the [Eurasian Plate](/Eurasian_Plate). &#91;171&#93; These dual processes, powered by convection currents within the Earth's [mantle](/Mantle_(geology)), were responsible for both the creation of the Indian Ocean and the eventual upward thrust of India's [continental crust](/Continental_crust) against Eurasia, leading to the dramatic uplift of the [Himalayas](/Himalayas). &#91;171&#93; Immediately south of these rising mountains, plate movement generated a vast, crescent-shaped [trough](/Trough_(geology)) that was rapidly filled with sediment carried by rivers, forming what is now the [Indo-Gangetic Plain](/Indo-Gangetic_Plain). &#91;172&#93; &#91;173&#93; The original Indian plate makes its first visible appearance above this sediment in the ancient [Aravalli range](/Aravalli_range), which extends from the [Delhi Ridge](/Delhi_Ridge) in a southwesterly direction. To its west lies the [Thar Desert](/Thar_Desert), its eastern reach curtailed by the Aravallis. &#91;174&#93; &#91;175&#93; &#91;176&#93;

The remainder of the Indian Plate constitutes [peninsular India](/South_India), the oldest and geologically most stable region of the country. It extends northward to the [Satpura](/Satpura_Range) and [Vindhya](/Vindhya_Range) ranges in central India. These parallel mountain chains stretch from the Arabian Sea coast in Gujarat in the west to the mineral-rich [Chota Nagpur Plateau](/Chota_Nagpur_Plateau) in Jharkhand in the east. &#91;177&#93; Further south, the remaining peninsular landmass, the [Deccan Plateau](/Deccan_Plateau), is bordered on the west and east by the coastal mountain ranges known as the [Western](/Western_Ghats) and [Eastern Ghats](/Eastern_Ghats); &#91;178&#93; the plateau itself contains some of the country's most ancient rock formations, with some dating back over a billion years. Formed in this manner, India is situated north of the equator, spanning latitudes between 6° 44′ and 35° 30′ north &#91;m&#93; and longitudes between 68° 7′ and 97° 25′ east. &#91;179&#93;

India's coastline stretches for 7,517 kilometers (4,700 mi); of this total, 5,423 kilometers (3,400 mi) belong to peninsular India, while the remaining 2,094 kilometers (1,300 mi) are attributed to the island chains of the Andaman, Nicobar, and Lakshadweep. &#91;180&#93; According to the hydrographic charts of the Indian navy, the [mainland coastline](/Coastal_India) is composed of: 43% sandy beaches, 11% rocky shores including cliffs, and 46% [mudflats](/Mudflat) or marshy shores. &#91;180&#93; Major rivers originating in the Himalayas, which flow significantly through India, include the [Ganges](/Ganges) and the [Brahmaputra](/Brahmaputra_River), both of which eventually discharge into the [Bay of Bengal](/Bay_of_Bengal). &#91;181&#93;

Key tributaries feeding the Ganges include the [Yamuna](/Yamuna) and the [Kosi](/Kosi_River). The Kosi's extremely gentle gradient, a result of long-term silt deposition, frequently leads to severe flooding and significant shifts in its course. &#91;182&#93; &#91;183&#93; Major peninsular rivers, whose steeper gradients prevent significant flooding, include the [Godavari](/Godavari_River), the [Mahanadi](/Mahanadi_River), the [Kaveri](/Kaveri_River), and the [Krishna](/Krishna_River), all of which also drain into the Bay of Bengal; &#91;184&#93; and the [Narmada](/Narmada_River) and the [Tapti](/Tapti_River), which flow into the [Arabian Sea](/Arabian_Sea). &#91;185&#93; Coastal features of note include the marshy expanse of the [Rann of Kutch](/Rann_of_Kutch) in western India and the alluvial delta of the [Sundarbans](/Sundarbans) in eastern India, the latter shared with Bangladesh. &#91;186&#93; India is home to two [archipelagos](/Archipelago): the [Lakshadweep](/Lakshadweep), comprised of [coral atolls](/Atoll) off India's southwestern coast; and the Andaman and Nicobar Islands, a volcanic chain situated in the [Andaman Sea](/Andaman_Sea). &#91;187&#93;

### Climate

India's climate is profoundly shaped by the imposing Himalayas and the arid Thar Desert, both of which exert considerable influence on the economically and culturally vital summer and winter [monsoons](/Monsoon). &#91;188&#93; The Himalayas act as a formidable barrier, preventing the frigid katabatic winds from Central Asia from penetrating the subcontinent, thereby maintaining warmer temperatures across most of India compared to other locations at similar latitudes. &#91;189&#93; &#91;190&#93; The Thar Desert plays a crucial role in attracting the moisture-laden south-westerly monsoon winds. Between June and October, these winds deliver the majority of India's annual rainfall. &#91;188&#93;

Four primary climatic classifications dominate India: [tropical wet](/Climate_of_India), [tropical dry](/Climate_of_India), [subtropical humid](/Climate_of_India), and [montane](/Climate_of_India). &#91;191&#93; Temperatures across India have shown an increase of 0.7 °C (1.3 °F) between 1901 and 2018. &#91;192&#93; [Climate change in India](/Climate_change_in_India) is widely considered to be the primary driver of this warming trend. The observed [retreat of Himalayan glaciers](/Retreat_of_glaciers_since_1850) has had a detrimental impact on the [flow rate](/Volumetric_flow_rate) of major Himalayan rivers, including the [Ganges](/Ganges) and the [Brahmaputra]. &#91;193&#93; According to some current projections, the frequency and intensity of droughts in India are expected to increase significantly by the end of the current century. &#91;194&#93;

### Biodiversity

India harbors the majority of the world's wild [tigers](/Tiger), with approximately 3,170 individuals recorded in 2022. &#91;195&#93;
A [chital](/Chital) ( *Axis axis* ) stag in [Nagarhole National Park](/Nagarhole_National_Park), situated in a region characterized by moderately dense &#91;n&#93; forest.
In 1948, three of the last remaining [Asiatic cheetahs](/Asiatic_cheetah) in India were tragically shot in the [Surguja district](/Surguja_district), [Madhya Pradesh](/Madhya_Pradesh), [Central India](/Central_India), by Maharajah [Ramanuj Pratap Singh Deo](/Ramanuj_Pratap_Singh_Deo). These young male cheetahs, all from the same litter, were resting together when they were killed at night.

India is recognized as a [megadiverse country](/Megadiverse_country), a designation reserved for 17 nations exhibiting exceptionally high [biological diversity](/Biological_diversity) and harboring numerous species that are exclusively [indigenous](/Indigenous_(ecology)), or [endemic](/Endemic), to their territories. &#91;196&#93; India serves as the [habitat](/Habitat) for 8.6% of all known [mammals](/Mammal), 13.7% of [bird](/Bird) species, 7.9% of [reptile](/Reptile) species, 6% of [amphibian](/Amphibian) species, 12.2% of [fish](/Fish) species, and 6.0% of all [flowering plant](/Flowering_plant) species found globally. &#91;197&#93; &#91;198&#93; A remarkable one-third of India's plant species are endemic. &#91;199&#93; Furthermore, India encompasses four of the world's 34 designated [biodiversity hotspots](/Biodiversity_hotspot), &#91;70&#93; which are biogeographical regions characterized by significant habitat loss alongside a high degree of endemism. &#91;o&#93; &#91;200&#93;

India's most densely forested regions, such as the [tropical moist forest](/Tropical_and_subtropical_moist_broadleaf_forest) found in the [Andaman Islands](/Andaman_Islands), the [Western Ghats](/Western_Ghats), and [Northeast India](/Northeast_India), cover approximately 3% of its land area. &#91;201&#93; &#91;202&#93; Moderately dense forests, defined by a canopy density ranging between 40% and 70%, extend across 9.39% of India's territory. &#91;201&#93; &#91;202&#93; These forests are predominant in the [temperate coniferous forest](/Temperate_coniferous_forest) zones of the [Himalayas](/Himalaya), the moist deciduous [sal](/Shorea_robusta) forests of eastern India, and the dry deciduous [teak](/Teak) forests of central and southern India. &#91;203&#93; India features two natural zones of [thorn forest](/Deserts_and_xeric_shrublands): one situated in the [Deccan Plateau](/Deccan_Plateau), to the east of the Western Ghats, and the other in the western sector of the Indo-Gangetic plain, which has since been transformed into highly productive agricultural land through extensive irrigation, rendering its original thorn forest features virtually invisible. &#91;204&#93; Among the notable indigenous trees of the Indian subcontinent are the [astringent](/Astringent) [Azadirachta indica](/Azadirachta_indica), commonly known as neem, widely utilized in rural Indian [herbal medicine], &#91;205&#93; and the luxuriant [Ficus religiosa](/Ficus_religiosa), or peepul tree, &#91;206&#93; which is depicted on the ancient seals unearthed at [Mohenjo-daro], &#91;207&#93; and beneath which, according to the [Pali canon](/P%C4%81li_Canon), [the Buddha](/Gautama_Buddha) attained enlightenment. &#91;208&#93;

A significant portion of India's flora and fauna are descendants of species originating from [Gondwana](/Gondwana), the southern [supercontinent](/Supercontinent) from which India separated more than 100 million years ago. &#91;209&#93; India's subsequent collision with Eurasia triggered a massive exchange of species. However, geological events such as [volcanism](/Deccan_Traps) and shifts in [climatic changes](/Climate_variability_and_change) later led to the extinction of numerous endemic Indian species. &#91;210&#93; Subsequently, mammals migrated into India from Asia through two [zoogeographic](/Zoogeography) corridors flanking the Himalayas. &#91;211&#93; This influx resulted in a reduction of endemism among India's mammal populations, which stands at 12.6%, in contrast to the much higher rates observed among reptiles (45.8%) and amphibians (55.8%). &#91;198&#93; Among the endemic species are the vulnerable &#91;212&#93; [hooded leaf monkey](/Nilgiri_Langur) &#91;213&#93; and the threatened [Beddome's toad](/Duttaphrynus_beddomii) &#91;214&#93; &#91;215&#93;, both found in the Western Ghats.

India is home to 172 [IUCN](/World_Conservation_Union)-designated [threatened animal species](/List_of_endangered_animals_in_India), representing 2.9% of all endangered forms globally. &#91;216&#93; These include the endangered [Bengal tiger](/Bengal_tiger) and the [Ganges river dolphin](/South_Asian_river_dolphin). Among the [critically endangered](/Critically_endangered) species are the [gharial](/Gharial), a unique [crocodilian](/Crocodilian); the [great Indian bustard](/Great_Indian_bustard); and the [Indian white-rumped vulture](/White-rumped_vulture), which has faced near extinction due to ingesting the carrion of cattle treated with the veterinary drug [diclofenac](/Diclofenac). &#91;217&#93; Prior to their extensive conversion for agriculture and clearance for human settlement, the thorn forests of Punjab were interspersed with open grasslands that supported large herds of [blackbuck](/Blackbuck_Conservation_Area), preyed upon by the [Asiatic cheetah](/Asiatic_cheetah); the blackbuck, now extinct in Punjab, is severely endangered in India, and the cheetah has vanished entirely from the country. &#91;218&#93; The pervasive and ecologically destructive encroachment by humans in recent decades has critically endangered India's wildlife. In response, the system of [national parks](/National_parks_of_India) and [protected areas](/Protected_areas_of_India), initially established in 1935, has undergone substantial expansion. In 1972, India enacted the [Wildlife Protection Act](/Wildlife_Protection_Act_of_1972) &#91;219&#93; and launched [Project Tiger](/Project_Tiger) to safeguard vital wilderness areas; the Forest Conservation Act followed in 1980, with amendments added in 1988. &#91;220&#93; India hosts [more than five hundred wildlife sanctuaries](/Wildlife_sanctuaries_of_India) and [eighteen biosphere reserves](/Biosphere_reserves_of_India), &#91;221&#93; four of which are integrated into the [World Network of Biosphere Reserves](/World_Network_of_Biosphere_Reserves); its [eighty-nine wetlands](/List_of_Ramsar_sites_in_India) are officially registered under the [Ramsar Convention](/Ramsar_Convention). &#91;222&#93;

### Government and politics

**Politics**

As part of the [Janadesh 2007](/Janadesh_2007) movement, 25,000 landless individuals advocating for [land reform](/Land_reform_in_India) listen to [Rajagopal P. V.](/Rajagopal_P._V.) in [Madhya Pradesh](/Madhya_Pradesh). &#91;223&#93;
US President [Barack Obama](/Barack_Obama) addresses the [members](/Member_of_Parliament_(India)) of the [Parliament of India](/Parliament_of_India) in [New Delhi](/New_Delhi) in November 2010.

India operates as a [parliamentary republic](/Parliamentary_republic) characterized by a [multi-party system](/Multi-party_system). &#91;224&#93; It recognizes six [national parties](/List_of_political_parties_in_India), including the [Indian National Congress](/Indian_National_Congress) (widely known as the Congress) and the [Bharatiya Janata Party](/Bharatiya_Janata_Party) (BJP), alongside over 50 [regional parties](/List_of_political_parties_in_India). &#91;225&#93; The Congress is generally considered to occupy the [ideological centre](/Centrism) within India's [political culture], &#91;226&#93; while the BJP aligns with [right-wing](/Right-wing_politics) to [far-right](/Far-right_politics) ideologies. &#91;227&#93; &#91;228&#93; &#91;229&#93; From 1950 until the late 1980s, the Congress consistently held a majority in [India's parliament](/Parliament_of_India). Subsequently, it began to share power more frequently with the BJP, &#91;230&#93; as well as with influential regional parties, which necessitated the formation of multi-party [coalition governments](/Coalition_government) at the national level. &#91;231&#93;

In the general elections held in [1951](/1951_Indian_general_election), [1957](/1957_Indian_general_election), and [1962](/1962_Indian_general_election), the Congress, under the leadership of [Jawaharlal Nehru](/Jawaharlal_Nehru), secured decisive victories. Following Nehru's death in 1964, [Lal Bahadur Shastri](/Lal_Bahadur_Shastri) briefly held the prime ministerial office; he was succeeded in 1966 by Nehru's daughter, [Indira Gandhi](/Indira_Gandhi), who led the Congress to election triumphs in [1967](/1967_Indian_general_election) and [1971](/1971_Indian_general_election). Public dissatisfaction with the [state of emergency](/The_Emergency_(India)) declared by Indira Gandhi in 1975 led to the Congress being ousted from power in the [1977](/1977_Indian_general_election) elections; the [Janata Party](/Janata_Party), which had opposed the emergency measures, was voted into government. Its tenure lasted two years, with [Morarji Desai](/Morarji_Desai) and [Charan Singh](/Charan_Singh) serving as prime ministers. After the Congress returned to power in 1980, Indira Gandhi was tragically [assassinated](/Assassination_of_Indira_Gandhi) and succeeded by her son, [Rajiv Gandhi](/Rajiv_Gandhi), who achieved a comfortable victory in the elections held [later that year](/1984_Indian_general_election). A [National Front](/National_Front_(India)) coalition, led by the [Janata Dal](/Janata_Dal) in alliance with the [Left Front](/Communist_Party_of_India_(Marxist)), emerged victorious in the [1989 elections](/1989_Indian_general_election); the subsequent government lasted just under two years, with [V.P. Singh](/V.P._Singh) and [Chandra Shekhar](/Chandra_Shekhar) serving as prime ministers. &#91;232&#93; In the [1991 Indian general election](/1991_Indian_general_election), the Congress, as the largest single party, formed a [minority government](/Minority_government) led by [P. V. Narasimha Rao](/P._V._Narasimha_Rao). &#91;233&#93;

Following the [1996 Indian general election](/1996_Indian_general_election), the BJP formed a government for a brief period; this was succeeded by [United Front](/United_Front_(India,_1996)) coalitions, which relied on external political backing. Two prime ministers held office during this period: [H.D. Deve Gowda](/H.D._Deve_Gowda) and [I.K. Gujral](/I.K._Gujral). In [1998](/1998_Indian_general_election), the BJP formed a coalition known as the [National Democratic Alliance](/National_Democratic_Alliance) (NDA). Under the leadership of [Atal Bihari Vajpayee](/Atal_Bihari_Vajpayee), the NDA became the first non-Congress coalition government to complete a full five-year term. &#91;234&#93; In the [2004 Indian general elections](/2004_Indian_general_election), no single party secured an absolute majority. Nevertheless, the Congress emerged as the largest party, forming another successful coalition: the [United Progressive Alliance](/United_Progressive_Alliance) (UPA). This alliance garnered support from [left-leaning](/Left-wing_politics) parties and members of parliament who opposed the BJP. The UPA was returned to power in the [2009 general election](/2009_Indian_general_election) with an increased number of seats, no longer requiring external support from [India's communist parties](/List_of_Communist_Parties_in_India). &#91;235&#93; [Manmohan Singh](/Manmohan_Singh) became the first prime minister since [Jawaharlal Nehru](/Jawaharlal_Nehru) in [1957](/1957_Indian_general_election) and [1962](/1962_Indian_general_election) to be re-elected for a consecutive five-year term. &#91;236&#93; In the [2014 general election](/2014_Indian_general_election), the BJP became the first political party since 1984 to achieve an absolute majority. &#91;237&#93; The BJP secured an absolute majority again in the [2019 general election](/2019_Indian_general_election). In the [2024 general election](/2024_Indian_general_election), a BJP-led NDA coalition successfully [formed the government](/Third_Modi_ministry). [Narendra Modi](/Narendra_Modi), a former [chief minister](/Chief_minister_(India)) of [Gujarat](/Gujarat), is now serving his third term as Prime Minister of India, holding the position since May 26, 2014. &#91;238&#93;

**Government**

[Rashtrapati Bhavan](/Rashtrapati_Bhavan), the official residence of the [President of India](/President_of_India), was conceived by British architects [Edwin Lutyens](/Edwin_Lutyens) and [Herbert Baker](/Herbert_Baker) for the [Viceroy of India](/Viceroy_of_India), and its construction spanned from 1911 to 1931 during the period of the [British Raj](/British_Raj). &#91;239&#93;

India functions as a [federation](/Federation) with a [parliamentary system](/Parliamentary_system) governed by the [Constitution of India](/Constitution_of_India). The principle of [federalism in India](/Federalism_in_India) delineates the division of powers between the central union and the individual [states](/States_and_territories_of_India). India's governmental structure, often described as "quasi-federal" with a strong central authority and comparatively weaker states, &#91;240&#93; has evolved towards a more federal character since the late 1990s, influenced by significant political, economic, and social transformations. &#91;241&#93; &#91;242&#93;

The Government of India is structured into three distinct branches: the [Executive](/Executive_(government)), the [Legislature](/Legislature), and the [Judiciary](/Judiciary). &#91;243&#93; The [President of India](/President_of_India) serves as the ceremonial [head of state], &#91;244&#93; elected indirectly for a five-year term by an [electoral college](/Electoral_College_(India)) composed of members from both national and state legislatures. &#91;245&#93; &#91;246&#93; The [Prime Minister of India](/Prime_Minister_of_India) functions as the [head of government] and wields the majority of [executive power](/Executive_(government)). &#91;247&#93; Appointed by the president, &#91;248&#93; the prime minister is supported by the political [party](/Political_party) or [political alliance](/Political_alliance) that commands a majority in the lower house of parliament. &#91;247&#93; The executive branch of the Indian government comprises the president, the [vice-president](/Vice_President_of_India), and the [Union Council of Ministers](/Union_Council_of_Ministers)—with the [cabinet](/Cabinet_(government)) acting as its executive committee—all headed by the prime minister. Crucially, any minister holding a portfolio must be a member of either house of parliament. &#91;244&#93; Within India's parliamentary framework, the executive is subordinate to the legislature; the prime minister and their council are directly accountable to the lower house of parliament. Permanent civil servants act as the executive's administrative arm, responsible for implementing all government decisions. &#91;249&#93;

India's legislature is a [bicameral](/Bicameralism) body known as the [parliament](/Parliament_of_India). Operating within a [Westminster-style](/Westminster_system) parliamentary framework, it consists of an upper house, the [Rajya Sabha](/Rajya_Sabha) (Council of States), and a lower house, the [Lok Sabha](/Lok_Sabha) (House of the People). &#91;250&#93; The Rajya Sabha is a permanent institution with 245 members serving staggered six-year terms, with elections occurring every two years. &#91;251&#93; The majority of these members are indirectly elected by the legislative bodies of the [states and union territories](/States_and_union_territories_of_India) in proportion to their respective state's population share within the national demographic. &#91;248&#93; The Lok Sabha comprises 543 members who are directly elected by popular vote from among citizens aged 18 and above; &#91;252&#93; they represent [single-member constituencies](/Single-member_constituency) and serve five-year terms. &#91;253&#93; A specific number of seats within each state are reserved for candidates belonging to [Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes](/Scheduled_Castes_and_Scheduled_Tribes), allocated in accordance with their population proportion within that state. &#91;252&#93;

India possesses a three-tiered system of [independent judiciary](/Judicial_independence), consisting of the [Supreme Court of India], presided over by the [Chief Justice of India], 25 [High Courts](/High_courts_of_India), and a substantial number of trial courts. &#91;254&#93; The Supreme Court holds [original jurisdiction] over cases pertaining to [fundamental rights](/Fundamental_rights_in_India) and disputes between states and the central government. It also possesses [appellate jurisdiction] over decisions rendered by the high courts. &#91;255&#93; Furthermore, it has the authority to invalidate both union and state laws that contravene the constitution, &#91;256&#93; as well as to nullify any government action deemed unconstitutional. &#91;257&#93;

### Administrative divisions

India is structured as a federal union, encompassing 28 [states](/States_and_union_territories_of_India) and 8 [union territories]. &#91;12&#93; All states, along with the union territories of [Jammu and Kashmir](/Jammu_and_Kashmir_(union_territory)), [Puducherry](/Puducherry_(union_territory)), and the [National Capital Territory of Delhi](/Delhi), feature elected legislatures and governments that operate under the [Westminster system](/Westminster_system). The remaining five union territories are administered directly by the central government through appointed officials. In 1956, through the [States Reorganisation Act](/States_Reorganisation_Act,_1956), states were reorganized based on linguistic demarcations. &#91;258&#93; The country has over a quarter of a million local government bodies operating at various levels, including city, town, block, district, and village. &#91;259&#93;

